# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: frankie-frisch
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:frankie-frisch/1919-major-league-baseball-season] The **1919 major league baseball season** began on April 19, 1919.
[src:frankie-frisch/1919-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 29, with the Cincinnati Reds and Chicago White Sox as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:frankie-frisch/1919-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 16th World Series, known for the infamous Black Sox Scandal, on October 1 and ended with Game 8 on October 9.
[src:frankie-frisch/1919-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Reds defeated the Chicago White Sox, five games to three, capturing their first championship in franchise history.
[src:frankie-frisch/1919-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Boston Red Sox from the 1918 season.
[src:frankie-frisch/1919-major-league-baseball-season] The Black Sox Scandal, for which the 1919 season is best remembered for, saw the Chicago White Sox throw (purposely lose) the World Series to the Cincinnati Reds, 5–3, in order to illegally gain money from gambling.
[src:frankie-frisch/1919-major-league-baseball-season] This scandal resulted in the dissolution of the National Baseball Commission and the creation of the office of the Commissioner of Baseball.
[src:frankie-frisch/1919-major-league-baseball-season] The new commissioner, Kenesaw Mountain Landis, banned eight players from baseball for life.
[src:frankie-frisch/1919-major-league-baseball-season] The 1919 schedule consisted of 140 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:frankie-frisch/1919-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:frankie-frisch/1919-major-league-baseball-season] This 140-game schedule format had been previously used in 1903.
[src:frankie-frisch/1919-major-league-baseball-season] The 154-game schedule was re-instituted for the 1920 season.
[src:frankie-frisch/1919-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 19, when the Brooklyn Robins defeated the Boston Braves 5–2 at Braves Field in the first game of a doubleheader.
[src:frankie-frisch/1919-major-league-baseball-season] American League Opening Day (and most other National League teams' Opening Day) wouldn't take place until April 23, where each league saw six of their teams play.
[src:frankie-frisch/1919-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the trend from the previous season which saw both leagues' Opening Day start on different days.
[src:frankie-frisch/1919-major-league-baseball-season] The National League regular season ended on September 28, while the American League regular season ended on September 29 with the New York Yankees defeating the Philadelphia Athletics 4–2 at Shibe Park.
[src:frankie-frisch/1919-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season since 1915 which saw both leagues end on different days, as well as the first season since 1903 that saw the leagues begin and conclude on different days.
[src:frankie-frisch/1919-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series would begin in Cincinnati on October 1, before concluding on October 9.
[src:frankie-frisch/1919-major-league-baseball-season] The minor leagues withdrew from the National Agreement, resulting in the abolition of the Rule 5 draft, as well as all existing optional agreements between major- and minor-league teams.
[src:frankie-frisch/1919-major-league-baseball-season] The only way in which major-league clubs could acquire players from the minors was by directly purchasing their contracts.
[src:frankie-frisch/1919-major-league-baseball-season] This change resulted in the previous $2,500 (equivalent to $46,400 in 2025) draft fee cap being removed.
[src:frankie-frisch/1919-major-league-baseball-season] 5 tie games (3 in AL, 2 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:frankie-frisch/1919-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 1 and ended on October 9 with the Cincinnati Reds defeating the Chicago White Sox in the 1919 World Series in eight games.
[src:frankie-frisch/1919-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-new-york-giants-season] The **1921 New York Giants season** was the franchise's 39th season, which culminated in the Giants defeating the New York Yankees in the World Series.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] The **1921 World Series** was the championship series in Major League Baseball for the 1921 season.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] The 18th edition of the World Series, it matched the National League (NL) champion New York Giants and the American League (AL) champion New York Yankees.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] The Series matched two distinct teams in strategy with the Giants, dedicated practitioners of the dead-ball era's "inside game" and the Yankees, who relied on the "power game" exemplified by Babe Ruth, who was coming off of what was arguably his best year ever statistically.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] This was the first World Series appearance by the Yankees, who have gone on to play in the Series a record 41 times.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] The 1921 Series was a closely contested matchup that ended on a double play featuring a baserunning miscue.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] It was also the last of four World Series to use the best-of-nine format, which had been used in the 1903, 1919, and the 1920 editions.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] The following year, the World Series permanently switched to a best-of-seven game format where it has remained ever since.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] It was also the first World Series to be broadcast over radio.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] The Series was the last of the experimental best-five-of-nine series, which the Giants won five games to three.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] This marked the first time in World Series history that the series occurred at a single site.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] It happened again the following year in the same place with the same two teams, in 1944 at St.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] Louis' Sportsman's Park between the Cardinals and the Browns, and then again in 2020 when the COVID-19 pandemic necessitated the first-ever neutral-site Series played at Globe Life Field in Arlington, Texas between the Los Angeles Dodgers and Tampa Bay Rays.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] For New Yorkers, this was the first subway Series in World Series history.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] It was also the first World Series to be broadcast on radio, with Grantland Rice covering the games live through Pittsburgh's KDKA.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] It was rebroadcast on WBZ in Massachusetts.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] Announcer Tommy Cowan also recreated the games over Westinghouse-owned WJZ in Newark as he listened to phoned-in reports from the stadium.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] Because of an infected arm and a bad knee (which he wrenched in Game 5), Babe Ruth did not start the final three games, appearing only as a pinch-hitter in the final inning of Game 8.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] Following the Series, Ruth and Bob Meusel did some postseason barnstorming, against the rules for Series participants at that time.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] Both were suspended for a number of games at the start of the 1922 season.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] Ruth filed a personal appeal with Commissioner Landis, who upheld their suspensions but agreed to rescind the rule effective the end of that season.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] Miller, described as "a big baseball fan" by *The New York Times*, made plans to attend games as a guest of the Commissioner of Baseball.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] The Series drew fans to New York City from across the continent, from as far west as California and Mexico to as far south as Cuba.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] Hotels were booked up, and both the New York Central and Pennsylvania Railroads made plans to add cars and run their trains in sections if necessary to handle the extra traffic expected.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] Davis, then the Governor of Ohio, was expected to attend the games as were several other VIPs of the time.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] The two were teammates on the old Baltimore Orioles in earlier seasons.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] Several players on both teams didn't start the 1921 season with either the Giants or the Yankees, and several others moved to other teams during the regular season earlier that year.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] For the Giants, Johnny Rawlings, Irish Meusel, Casey Stengel and Red Causey started the season as Philadelphia Phillies, who finished last in the National League that year.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] Outfielder Bill Cunningham had played for the Seattle Rainiers of the Pacific Coast League, nor did Cozy Dolan or Red Shea start the season with the Giants, while the Yankees acquired outfielder Elmer Miller and pitcher Tom Rogers during the season.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] Nonparticipants from either team in the Series included Curt Walker, Lee King, Johnny Monroe, Rube Benton, Goldie Rapp, Ping Bodie, Tom Sheehan and Tom Connelly.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] This was the first of three consecutive matchups between the Yankees and Giants (1921–1923) and marked the only time (as of 2023) that three straight World Series featured the same two clubs.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] Brothers Bob and Irish Meusel played against each other in each of those three series, making them the first set of brothers to play against each other on opposing teams in a World Series or any Big Four championship series.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] Mays pitched a complete game 5-hit shutout, Frankie Frisch getting 4 of those hits off of Mays in a losing cause for the Giants.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] This was the first World Series game victory for the Yankees.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] Pitching Ruth carefully, the Giants walked the Babe three times; but after the third walk he stole second and then third base, much to the delight of Yankee fans.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] But when he slid into third, he scraped his elbow severely and the site became infected.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] Hoyt held the Giants to two hits, the Yankees jumping to a 2–0 lead in the series.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] After getting outscored 6–0 in the first two games of this series and falling behind 4–0 in the top of the third, the Giants tied it with four runs of their own in the bottom half.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] Later on, an 8-run 7th inning highlighted by Ross Youngs' bases loaded triple turned the tide as the Giants got their first win of this series.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] Ruth was taken out in the eighth after again scraping his elbow sliding into a base.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] The Yankees announced after the game that the elbow would have to be lanced and that he would not return for the rest of the Series.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] Ruth suited up, but stayed on the bench during batting practice.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] When the game began, however, to everyone's surprise, he popped out of the dugout and jogged to his outfield position.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] He kept touching his bandaged arm throughout the game.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] Despite the injury, he got two hits including a ninth-inning homer, his first World Series home run as well as the first World Series home run in Yankees franchise history.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] But the Giants won the game and tied the series at 2–2.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] Ruth's arm was still bandaged, but he played again.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] In the fourth, with the score tied 1–1, he shocked everyone by bunting and beating it out.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] His teammate Meusel then doubled, scoring Ruth all the way from first base for the go-ahead run in a 3–1 Yankee win.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] The Giants battled back from 3–0 and 5–3 deficits to take Game 6.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] Phil Douglas scattered eight hits and held the Yankees to one run, the Giants winning 2–1 on Frank Snyder's RBI double in the seventh inning.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] Facing elimination, Yankee manager Miller Huggins sent Ruth out to pinch-hit in the bottom of the ninth.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] The Babe, nursing both elbow and knee injuries, had sat out this game and missed all of Games 6 and 7.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] The bases were empty and the Yankees still trailed by the lone run of the game scored by the Giants in the top of the first.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] A HR would tie the game, and a hit or a walk would give the Yankees a chance.
[src:frankie-frisch/1921-world-series] But Ruth grounded out, and shortly afterwards Frank Baker hit into a double play after a walk by Aaron Ward who was thrown out at third base for the final out of the Series, giving the Giants their first world championship since Christy Mathewson's record three complete shutouts in 1905.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-new-york-giants-season] The **1922 New York Giants season** was the franchise's 40th season.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-new-york-giants-season] The team finished in first place in the National League with a 93–61 record.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-new-york-giants-season] The Giants won their second consecutive World Series, defeating the New York Yankees in five games (Game 2 was a 3–3 tie) without a loss.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] The **1922 World Series** was the championship series in Major League Baseball for the 1922 season.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] The 19th edition of the World Series, it matched the National League (NL) champion New York Giants against the American League (AL) champion New York Yankees.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] The Giants beat the Yankees in five games (four games to zero, with one tie) in the first Series with a permanent best-of-seven format.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] By now, the term "World Series" was being used frequently, as opposed to "World's Series".
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] The Giants held Babe Ruth in check (he batted only .118 with just one RBI) and scored just enough runs to win each of the games outside the controversial Game 2 tie.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] That game was called on account of darkness, but many thought there was sufficient light to have played some more innings (the sun was still in the sky), and there were some suspicions that one or both teams might have "allowed" the tie to happen to increase the overall gate receipts.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] Commissioner Landis was among those who was dissatisfied with the result.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] One story is that Landis asked Umpire Hildebrand, "Why the Sam Hill did you call the game?" The umpire answered, "There was a temporary haze on the field." The game decision was in the hands of the umpires, but the Commissioner's Office controlled the gate receipts.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] Landis ordered the money, more than $120,000, turned over to World War I charities, thus nullifying any impropriety.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] The tied game would turn out to be the third (and final) tied game in the history of the World Series.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] The other two tied games occurred in 1907 and 1912.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] No ties are possible under later rules, which allow for suspension of a tied game and resumption of it at a later date, as with Game 5 of the 2008 World Series.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] As of 2024, this is the last time the Giants have won the World Series at home, as their next five championships were all clinched on the road.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] This would prove to be Giants' manager John McGraw's third and final World Series win.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] The game and Series remained scoreless until the sixth inning.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] Whitey Witt tripled off of Art Nehf, then was cut down at home trying to score on a fielder's choice, but a Babe Ruth hit got the run home.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] The Yankees added another run next inning on Aaron Ward's sacrifice fly with runners on second and third.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] A three-run Giant rally in the eighth knocked out Yankee starter Bullet Joe Bush, who allowed four straight leadoff singles, the last of which to Irish Meusel scoring two. and the winning run coming off reliever Waite Hoyt on a Ross Youngs sacrifice fly.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] This was the controversial tie (see above).
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] Pitchers Bob Shawkey and Jesse Barnes went all 10 innings.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] The Giants scored all three runs in the first on Irish Meusel's three-run home run after two singles.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] The Yankees scored a run in the first on Wally Pipp's RBI single after Joe Dugan reached second on an error and another run in the fourth on Aaron Ward's home run.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] The Yankees had tied the game in the eighth on doubles by Babe Ruth and Bob Meusel, but that is the way the game ended.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] Knuckleballer Jack Scott kept the Yankees off the board.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] In the bottom of the third with runners on second and third, Frankie Frisch's sacrifice fly and Irish Meusel's RBI single scored a run each for the Giants, who added an insurance run in the seventh on Frankie Frisch's RBI single.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] This contest moved along even faster than Game 3.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] It was over in a snappy 1:41, with Giants pitcher Hugh McQuillan going the distance for a 4-3 win.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] The Yankees scored two runs in the first on back-to-back singles by Wally Pipp and Bob Meusel, but in the fifth after a leadoff single and double, Dave Bancroft's two-run single tied the game.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] After a single and groundout, Irish Meusel's groundout and Ross Youngs's RBI single scored a run each.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] Aaron Ward's home run in the seventh cut the Giants' lead to one, but the Yankees did not score after that.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] Art Nehf's five-hit pitching combined with a three-run eighth inning won the Series for the Giants.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] The Yankees scored a run in the first when Joe Dugan singled with one out, moved to second on a sacrifice bunt and scored on Wally Pipp's RBI single, but in the bottom of the second with runners on second and third, Bill Cunningham's two-run single gave the Giants the lead.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] The Yankees tied the game in the fifth on Bullet Joe Bush's RBI single after a walk and single, then took the lead on Everett Scott's sacrifice fly with runners on second and third.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] The decisive rally began with a Heinie Groh single and Frankie Frisch double.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] After an intentional walk to Ross Youngs, a two-run single by High Pockets Kelly put the Giants on top.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] The next batter, Lee King, inserted in the outfield that inning for defensive purposes, delivered an RBI single to make it 5-3, and that's how it ended.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] This was the second of three consecutive matchups between the Yankees and Giants (1921–1923) marked the only time (as of 2023), that three straight World Series featured the same two clubs.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] The Giants became the second NL team to win back-to-back World Series, following the Chicago Cubs in 1907–08, and remained the last until the 1975–76 Cincinnati Reds.
[src:frankie-frisch/1922-world-series] This also remains the last World Series to be won by the Giants at home, as their championships of 1933 and 1954 (for New York) and 2010, 2012 and 2014 (for San Francisco) were all clinched as the visiting team.
[src:frankie-frisch/1926-major-league-baseball-season] The **1926 major league baseball season** began on April 13, 1926.
[src:frankie-frisch/1926-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 29, with the St.
[src:frankie-frisch/1926-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals and New York Yankees as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:frankie-frisch/1926-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 23rd World Series on October 2 and ended with Game 7 on October 10.
[src:frankie-frisch/1926-major-league-baseball-season] The Cardinals defeated the Yankees, four games to three, capturing their first championship in franchise history.
[src:frankie-frisch/1926-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Pittsburgh Pirates from the 1925 season.
[src:frankie-frisch/1926-major-league-baseball-season] This was the fifth of eight seasons that "League Awards", a precursor to the Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award (introduced in 1931), were issued.
[src:frankie-frisch/1926-major-league-baseball-season] The 1926 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:frankie-frisch/1926-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 22 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:frankie-frisch/1926-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since the 1904 season (except for 1919) and would be used until 1961 in the American League and 1962 in the National League.
[src:frankie-frisch/1926-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day, April 13, featured all sixteen teams, continuing the trend which started with the 1924 season.
[src:frankie-frisch/1926-major-league-baseball-season] The American League would see its final day of the regular season on September 27, while the National League would see its final day of the regular season on September 29 with a doubleheader between the Philadelphia Phillies and Boston Braves.
[src:frankie-frisch/1926-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 2 and October 10.
[src:frankie-frisch/1926-major-league-baseball-season] 12 tie games (5 in AL, 7 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:frankie-frisch/1926-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 2 and ended on October 10 with the St.
[src:frankie-frisch/1926-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals defeating the New York Yankees in the 1926 World Series in seven games.
[src:frankie-frisch/1927-major-league-baseball-season] The **1927 major league baseball season** began on April 12, 1927.
[src:frankie-frisch/1927-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 2, with the Pittsburgh Pirates and New York Yankees as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:frankie-frisch/1927-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 24th World Series on October 5 and ended with Game 4 on October 8.
[src:frankie-frisch/1927-major-league-baseball-season] The Yankees swept the Pirates in four games, capturing their second championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1923.
[src:frankie-frisch/1927-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the St.
[src:frankie-frisch/1927-major-league-baseball-season] The New York Yankees, whose lineup featured Babe Ruth and Lou Gehrig of the famed "Murderers' Row," dominated the American League with 110 wins.
[src:frankie-frisch/1927-major-league-baseball-season] No no-hitters were thrown during the season.
[src:frankie-frisch/1927-major-league-baseball-season] This was the sixth of eight seasons that "League Awards", a precursor to the Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award (introduced in 1931), were issued.
[src:frankie-frisch/1927-major-league-baseball-season] The 1927 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:frankie-frisch/1927-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 12 with all but all but the Detroit Tigers and St.
[src:frankie-frisch/1927-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 2.
[src:frankie-frisch/1927-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 5 and October 8.
[src:frankie-frisch/1927-major-league-baseball-season] 8 tie games 5 in AL, 3 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:frankie-frisch/1927-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 5 and ended on October 8 with the New York Yankees sweeping the Pittsburgh Pirates in the 1927 World Series in four games.
[src:frankie-frisch/1927-major-league-baseball-season] In November 1926, following the conclusion of the previous season, Chicago Cubs owner William Wrigley Jr. renamed Cubs Park to Wrigley Field.
[src:frankie-frisch/1927-major-league-baseball-season] During a Philadelphia Phillies home game against the St.
[src:frankie-frisch/1927-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals at the Baker Bowl on May 14, parts of two sections of the lower deck extension along the right-field line collapsed due to rotted shoring timbers, triggered by an oversize gathering of people, who were seeking shelter from rain.
[src:frankie-frisch/1927-major-league-baseball-season] While no one died during the collapse, one individual died of heart failure in the subsequent stampede that injured 50.
[src:frankie-frisch/1927-major-league-baseball-season] The game was cut short in the 7th inning following the collapse.
[src:frankie-frisch/1927-major-league-baseball-season] In a similar situation to a partial collapse in 1903, the Phillies rented from the Philadelphia Athletics at Shibe Park while repairs were being made to the old structure.
[src:frankie-frisch/1927-major-league-baseball-season] The Phillies played 12 home games at Shibe Park, from May 16 to May 28, before eventually returning to the Baker Bowl on June 24 after spending nearly a month on the road.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] Born in The Bronx, New York City, Frisch attended Fordham Preparatory School, graduating in 1916.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] He went on to Fordham University where he continued to star in four sports: baseball, football, basketball, and track.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] His speed earned him the nickname "the Fordham Flash".
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] In 1919, Frisch left Fordham to sign with the New York Giants of the National League, moving directly to the majors without playing in the minor leagues.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] He made an immediate impact, finishing third in the NL in stolen bases and seventh in RBI in 1920, his first full season.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] Manager John McGraw was so impressed by Frisch that he soon named him team captain, advising him base-running and hitting.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] The Giants played Frisch at both third base and second base early in his career, but by 1923 he was installed as the team's full-time second baseman.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] Frisch batted over .300 in his last six seasons with New York.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] He was also an expert fielder and a skilled base-runner.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] In 1921, he led the National League with 48 steals, in 1923 in hits, and in 1924 in runs.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] With Frisch adding his fiery competitiveness to the team, the Giants won the World Series in 1921 and 1922, winning the NL pennant the following two seasons as well.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] On September 10, 1924, Frisch went 6-for-7 in a 22–1 rout of the Boston Braves at the Polo Grounds.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] Frisch is tied with Pablo Sandoval for the franchise post-season multi-hit games record of 15.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] After the 1926 season, Frisch was traded—with pitcher Jimmy Ring—to the St.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] Louis Cardinals in exchange for star Rogers Hornsby.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] After an August 1926 loss in which Frisch had missed a sign, costing the Giants a run, McGraw had loudly berated Frisch in front of the team; Frisch responded by leaving the team, and his previously close relationship with McGraw virtually ended.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] On June 2, 1930, in the 7th inning of a game against the Philadelphia Phillies, Frisch was spiked.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] The ailments he sustained sidelined him for several weeks, coming back for a game against those same Phillies on June 20.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] Playing second base for the Cardinals, Frisch appeared in four more World Series (1928, 1930–31, 1934), bringing his career total to eight.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] He was the driving force of the "Gashouse Gang", the nickname for the Cardinals clubs of the early 1930s, which were built around him to reflect his no-holds-barred approach.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] The Cardinals had won only one pennant before Frisch joined the team; the Giants would win the pennant only once in Frisch's nine seasons as the Cards' regular second baseman.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] Frisch played eleven seasons with the Cardinals.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] In 1931, he was voted the Most Valuable Player in the National League after batting .311 with 4 home runs, 82 RBI, and leading the League in stolen bases with 28.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] The 1931 Cardinals also triumphed in the World Series, defeating Connie Mack's defending two-time champion Philadelphia Athletics in seven games.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] Frisch became player-manager of the Cardinals in 1933 and was named to the NL's first three All-Star teams from 1933 to 1935.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] In 1934, he managed the Cardinals to another seven-game World Series victory—this time over the Detroit Tigers.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] Frisch finished his playing career in 1937.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] His career statistics totaled a .316 batting average, still the highest ever for a switch hitter, with 2,880 hits, 1532 runs, 466 doubles, 138 triples, 105 home runs, 728 walks, and 1,244 RBI over 2,311 games.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] He was difficult to strike out, fanning only 272 times in 9,112 at-bats, or once every 33.5 at-bats.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] He also stole 419 bases in his 19 MLB seasons.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] His hit total stood as the record for switch-hitters until Pete Rose surpassed it in 1977.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] Frisch also hit .300 for his career from both sides of the plate; the only other switch-hitter with more than 5,000 at-bats with this distinction is fellow Hall of Famer Chipper Jones.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] Frankie Frisch was elected to the Baseball Hall of Fame in 1947.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] After no players had been selected by the writers in the previous two years (the only elections since 1942), the rules were revised to limit eligibility to those players who had retired after 1921; Frisch was among the first four players to benefit from the more reasonable field of candidates.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] After his retirement as an active player, Frisch continued to manage the Cardinals, but was never able to capture another pennant.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] Frisch also had managerial stints with the Pittsburgh Pirates (1940–46) and the Chicago Cubs (1949–51), but without the success he had in St.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] Frisch's career ledger as a manager shows a 1,138–1,078 (.514) mark, including the pennant in 1934.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] He also spent the first two months of the 1949 season as a New York Giants' coach, working under his old double-play partner, Leo Durocher, before leaving June 14 to replace Charlie Grimm as manager of the Cubs.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] Frisch also worked for several years as a baseball color commentator on radio and television.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] In 1939, he called games for the Boston Bees and the Boston Red Sox on the Colonial Network, a regional radio network serving five New England states.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] He also called Giants radio in 1947–48, then worked as a post-game host for the team's telecasts in the 1950s.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] From 1959 to 1961, Frisch teamed with Jack Whitaker to form the backup crew for Saturday *Game of the Week* coverage on CBS.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] Critics have pointed out that many of these selectees had accomplishments which were less outstanding than those of other players who were bypassed, and were only selected because of Frisch's influence.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] Frisch died in Wilmington, Delaware from injuries suffered from a car accident near Elkton, Maryland a month earlier.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] Frisch had been returning to Rhode Island from the meeting of the Veterans Committee in Florida when he lost control of his car.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] Frisch died in the same manner as other N.Y.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] Giant Hall of Famers Mel Ott (1958) and Carl Hubbell (1988).
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] He is interred at Woodlawn Cemetery in the Bronx, New York City.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] During his lifetime, Frisch used 1898 as his year of birth, although other records (Social Security death index, Census records, World War I Draft registration, and passport application) indicate an 1897 birth.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] In 1999, he ranked number 88 on *The Sporting News* list of the 100 Greatest Baseball Players, and was a nominee for the Major League Baseball All-Century Team.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] In January 2014, the Cardinals announced Frisch among 22 former players and personnel to be inducted into the St.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] Louis Cardinals Hall of Fame Museum for the inaugural class of 2014.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] Years later, Nash added a footnote to this stanza: "p.s.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] For many years, he lived at 184 Fenimore Road in the Bonnie Crest neighborhood of New Rochelle, New York.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] He had two hounds named Flash and Patches who kept him company.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] Frisch eventually moved to Charlestown, Rhode Island, devoting himself mainly to his interests in gardening and classical music.
[src:frankie-frisch/frankie-frisch] The Mosholu Baseball Field in Bedford Park, Bronx, was renamed to Frank Frisch Field in 1948.
